<section class="section">
  <div class="container grid grid-2">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">Why Understanding Matters</p>
      <h2>Prevention starts before anyone enters the water.</h2>
    </div>
    <div>
      <p>Rip currents are one of the leading causes of drowning on the Great Lakes, yet they are widely misunderstood or overlooked. Unlike dramatic ocean waves, Great Lakes rip currents can form quickly, look deceptively calm, and occur on days when the water appears inviting.</p>
      <p>Understanding when, where, and why rip currents occur empowers people to make safer decisions before entering the water. It also helps communities, emergency responders, and decision-makers move from reactive rescue to proactive prevention.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-muted">
  <div class="container grid grid-2">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">The Story Behind This Project</p>
      <h2>Born from personal loss, lived experience, and preventable gaps.</h2>
    </div>
    <div>
      <p>The Rip Current Information Project was born out of personal loss, lived experience, and a growing frustration with preventable tragedies. After witnessing firsthand how little accurate, accessible information exists about Great Lakes rip currents, and how often warnings come too late, this project was created to close that gap.</p>
      <p>What began as one person asking hard questions has grown into a collaborative effort focused on translating science into practical, life-saving information. Clear communication, shared knowledge, and early awareness can change outcomes.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container grid grid-2">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">Who We Serve</p>
      <h2>Everyone who interacts with the Great Lakes.</h2>
    </div>
    <div>
      <p>We serve residents, visitors, families, anglers, paddlers, swimmers, and beachgoers of all ages. We also support first responders, municipalities, educators, and community organizations by providing reliable information that can inform safety messaging, policy, and on-the-ground decision-making.</p>
      <p>At our core, we serve people who may never realize they were at risk. If someone goes home safely because they understood the conditions that day, our work has done its job.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

